<td style="font-weight:bold;background-color:#f2f2f2"><a href="/wiki/Japan_Game_Awards" title="Japan Game Awards">Japan Game Awards</a></td>
<td style="background-color:#f2f2f2">Award for Excellence<sup id="cite_ref-award_49-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-award-49"><span>[</span>49<span>]</span></a></sup></td>
</tr>
</table>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>The game was heavily acclaimed in Japan for combining innovative gameplay with cinema-like story telling and character development on the back of Japan's <a href="/wiki/Organized_crime" title="Organized crime">criminal underground</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50"><span>[</span>50<span>]</span></a></sup> <i>Yakuza</i> received generally positive reviews among Western critics earning a 75 out of 100 in <a href="/wiki/Metacritic" title="Metacritic">Metacritic</a> and a 77.67% in <a href="/wiki/GameRankings" title="GameRankings">GameRankings</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Meta_38-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Meta-38"><span>[</span>38<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-gr_39-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gr-39"><span>[</span>39<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/IGN" title="IGN">IGN</a> praised its combat system and sense of style but criticized its tedious gameplay.<sup id="cite_ref-ignrev_47-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ignrev-47"><span>[</span>47<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Newtype_(magazine)" title="Newtype (magazine)" class="mw-redirect">Newtype USA</a> called it "the adult-themed spiritual successor to the Dreamcast's <a href="/wiki/Shenmue" title="Shenmue">Shenmue</a> series" and found that the fighting system would interest many players.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51"><span>[</span>51<span>]</span></a></sup> GamePro similarly compared it with <i>Shenmue</i> based on the amount of subscenarios.<sup id="cite_ref-gamepro_42-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gamepro-42"><span>[</span>42<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/1UP.com" title="1UP.com">1UP.com</a> saw the potential of the fighting as it often earned the player money which can be used to buy items in the city.<sup id="cite_ref-1uprev_1-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1uprev-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/GameRevolution" title="GameRevolution" class="mw-redirect">GameRevolution</a> criticized the number of random encounters which resulted in a large amount of loading times. He also criticized the simplicity of the fighting system and few notable issues<sup id="cite_ref-gamerevrev_43-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gamerevrev-43"><span>[</span>43<span>]</span></a></sup> with <a href="/wiki/GameTrailers" title="GameTrailers">GameTrailers</a> agreeing on the difficulty in centering on an enemy.<sup id="cite_ref-gametrailers_45-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gametrailers-45"><span>[</span>45<span>]</span></a></sup> The amount of sidequests available received generally favorable response.<sup id="cite_ref-gamepro_42-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gamepro-42"><span>[</span>42<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-gametrailers_45-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gametrailers-45"><span>[</span>45<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The game has been praised for the design of the city and delivery of the English voice acting.<sup id="cite_ref-1uprev_1-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1uprev-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> GameRevolution also praised it as "From an audio/video standpoint, Yakuza is exceptionally well-produced. Although the cut-scenes are all use the in-game engine, the complicated facial expressions are shockingly intricate and colorful, while some of the floral tattoos look too good to be true."<sup id="cite_ref-gamerevrev_43-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gamerevrev-43"><span>[</span>43<span>]</span></a></sup> UGO Networks praised the seriousness of the story as the game "respects and appreciates yakuza culture and its often forgotten roots in the samurai tradition/bushido code" and thus lammented the lack of the Japanese audio.<sup id="cite_ref-ugo_48-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ugo-48"><span>[</span>48<span>]</span></a></sup> GameTrailers also wished for a Japanese audio option, despite noting the English dub did a fine job.<sup id="cite_ref-gametrailers_45-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gametrailers-45"><span>[</span>45<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/GameZone" title="GameZone">GameZone</a> called it a "epic story that will keep you exploring the world filled with criminals and Kazuma's only friends who will help him along the way."<sup id="cite_ref-gamezone_46-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gamezone-46"><span>[</span>46<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The game sold 232,650 units in Japan during 2005.<sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52"><span>[</span>52<span>]</span></a></sup> In 2006 it shipped 345,323 units.<sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53"><span>[</span>53<span>]</span></a></sup> Due to its commercial success on the Japanese market, <i>Yakuza</i> had a PlayStation 2 the Best edition on October 26, 2006, and an exceptional reprint on December 6, 2007. In contrast, this Asian long seller title never had a <a href="/wiki/Platinum_Range" title="Platinum Range" class="mw-redirect">Platinum</a> or <a href="/wiki/List_of_Sony_Greatest_Hits_games" title="List of Sony Greatest Hits games" class="mw-redirect">Greatest Hits</a> re-release on the western markets. Total sales reached 1 million.<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54"><span>[</span>54<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Legacy">Legacy</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Yakuza_(video_game)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Legacy">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>According to Toshihiro Nagoshi "[Ryu ga Gotoku was successful] because there were only a few titles which directly portray original Japanese culture. Also, there is no other title which attempts to represent such a Japanese world view with a big budget title."<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55"><span>[</span>55<span>]</span></a></sup> The game was also recognized for excellence in the 2007 Japan Game Awards.<sup id="cite_ref-award_49-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-award-49"><span>[</span>49<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>A sequel, titled <i><a href="/wiki/Yakuza_2" title="Yakuza 2">Yakuza 2</a></i>, was released in Japan on December 7, <a href="/wiki/2006_in_video_gaming" title="2006 in video gaming">2006</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56"><span>[</span>56<span>]</span></a></sup> and in North America and Europe on September 9, <a href="/wiki/2008_in_video_gaming" title="2008 in video gaming">2008</a> and September 19, <a href="/wiki/2008_in_video_gaming" title="2008 in video gaming">2008</a> respectively.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57"><span>[</span>57<span>]</span></a></sup> The game was followed by <i>Ryu ga Gotoku</i> a <a href="/wiki/PlayStation_3" title="PlayStation 3">PlayStation 3</a> spin-off where the player controls Miyamoto Musashi, also known as Kiryu. Although this game did not make it to the west, the sequel <i><a href="/wiki/Yakuza_3" title="Yakuza 3">Yakuza 3</a></i> for the PlayStation 3<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58"><span>[</span>58<span>]</span></a></sup> It was then followed by <i><a href="/wiki/Yakuza_4" title="Yakuza 4">Yakuza 4</a></i> which for the first time incorporated multiple playable characters.<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59"><span>[</span>59<span>]</span></a></sup> The next game, the spin off <i><a href="/wiki/Yakuza:_Dead_Souls" title="Yakuza: Dead Souls">Yakuza: Dead Souls</a></i>, also made it to English releases,<i><a href="/wiki/Ryu_ga_Gotoku_5" title="Ryu ga Gotoku 5" class="mw-redirect">Ryu ga Gotoku 5</a></i> was announced to be released in Q3 2015 while <i><a href="/wiki/Ry%C5%AB_ga_Gotoku_Ishin!" title="Ryū ga Gotoku Ishin!">Ryū ga Gotoku Ishin!</a></i> remains as a Japan exclusive game.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Live-action_adaptations">Live-action adaptations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Yakuza_(video_game)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Live-action adaptations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="hatnote relarticle mainarticle">Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Like_a_Dragon:_Prologue" title="Like a Dragon: Prologue">Like a Dragon: Prologue</a> and <a href="/wiki/Like_a_Dragon" title="Like a Dragon">Like a Dragon</a></div>
<p>In 2006, <a href="/wiki/Takashi_Miike" title="Takashi Miike">Takashi Miike</a> directed a prequel <i><a href="/wiki/Like_a_Dragon:_Prologue" title="Like a Dragon: Prologue">Like a Dragon: Prologue</a></i> (龍が如く 〜序章〜, <i>ryu ga gotoku -joshou-</i>) with <a href="/wiki/Mixed_martial_artist" title="Mixed martial artist" class="mw-redirect">mixed martial artist</a> and <a href="/wiki/Puroresu" title="Puroresu">puroresu</a> wrestler <a href="/wiki/Masakatsu_Funaki" title="Masakatsu Funaki">Masakatsu Funaki</a> as Kazuma Kiryu. A film adaptation <i><a href="/wiki/Like_a_Dragon" title="Like a Dragon">Like a Dragon</a></i> (龍が如く 劇場版, <i>ryu ga gotoku: gekijoban</i>) was directed by <a href="/wiki/Takashi_Miike" title="Takashi Miike">Takashi Miike</a> in 2007. Kazuma Kiryu's role is played by actor <a href="/wiki/Kazuki_Kitamura" title="Kazuki Kitamura">Kazuki Kitamura</a> known overseas for his roles in <a href="/wiki/Shohei_Imamura" title="Shohei Imamura">Shohei Imamura</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/The_Eel_(film)" title="The Eel (film)">The Eel</a></i>, Takeshi Miike's <i><a href="/wiki/Dead_or_Alive_(film)" title="Dead or Alive (film)">Dead or Alive</a></i> and <a href="/wiki/Quentin_Tarantino" title="Quentin Tarantino">Quentin Tarantino</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Kill_Bill" title="Kill Bill">Kill Bill</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60"><span>[</span>60<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="References">References</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Yakuza_(video_game)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: References">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
